     <font class="TallRed">The importance of facts<a name="108743049972887184">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          Oy TuuK, how about investing in some paragraphs? I hear they're priced to move in bulk, and very easy to use. And they have the most intuitive interface after the nipple (and before MacOS X). Okay, time to correct some things in your rant. Good work on it, by the way, it's nice and long. However, there's a few problems with it.<br /><br />First, the deteriorating CDs thing is bunk. I've got many CDs in my collection (bought by my father) from 1986 that are still in perfect condition, nearly 18 years after their pressings—and that's with heavy but careful use in stereo CD players, long before computers could handle compression and playback of CD-quality audio. Compact discs that DO deteriorate are CD-Rs, due to the cheapness of the materials involved. However, pressed CDs (the silver kind you buy) will last effectively forever (MANY generations of hardware into the future). The only pressed CDs that WILL deteriorate are VERY early CDs (from the early 1980s) which used inks that ate away at the top polycarbonate layer or had aluminum layers which extended all the way to the edge of the discs. Any CD made after about 1984 or so does not have either of these problems.<br /><br />Secondly, the cost of CDs isn't just because record companies are greedy (though that does have to do with it)—it's more a result of the broken way in which record companies spend their money looking for and hiring talent. The truth is it doesn't take as much as you'd think to get "signed." The problem is how the record companies go about business after that. In order for an artist to record, mix, and master an album in a professional studio, they need lots of money, money they often cannot raise themselves. When an artist is signed, the record company loans them the money necessary to record the album and distribute it. Then the artist is responsible for paying that loan back, through profits obtained from the album being sold and/or touring if the album doesn't sell well enough. Only the very biggest bands (a very tiny proportion of those signed) make royalty profits from their work—at most 5%, usually around 1 - 2%. Even then, the record companies keep much of THEIR money because they have to subsidize all the artists who didn't sell. This subsidizing system is what keeps only but a very few artists from becoming incredibly successful. As a result, only these bands or artists are marketed heavily, leading to the homogenization of the radio airwaves and music in general.<br /><br />The real answer is that the record company system and all the baggage that's come along with it is fundamentally broken. So yes, they are afraid of the Internet, but not because CD sales are down. In fact, any independent study will show that CD sales have been on the rise recently. The reason record companies are afraid of the Internet (and thus forcing online music distributors to DRM their wares) is because it represents a fundamental shift in power away from the big faceless industry and more towards truly innovative artists.<br /><br />Finally, your assertion that someone in their home can record music at higher quality than most professional studio albums of the past is wishful thinking. Maybe your ears can't hear the difference between audio recorded on a prosumer-grade 16-bit, 44KHz sound card and mastered at that level throughout, but mine certainly can. Studios are built to incredibly detailed specifications, utilizing only the best in microphones and digital (or analogue) recording equipment. Modern albums are recorded, mixed, and mastered at 24-bit, 192KHz, and downsampled for distribution on CD. Compressed music has beaten the public's ears into submission; 128Kbps MP3 is NOT CD-quality by any stretch of the imagination. Is it good enough to fool most people? Yes, but it certainly doesn't rival the production quality of, say, <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/B00005ASHM/qid=1087429739/sr=8-1/ref=pd_ka_1/102-4999834-1113746?v=glance&s=music&n=507846" target="_new">the album by which all others are judged</a>, recorded long before digital hit the scene. Well-maintained vinyl played on hi-fi equipment can easily rival the sound of CDs played on equipment of much higher price.<br /><br />All that aside, I'm of the opinion that the American music world won't be redeemed of the mass-produced dreck that has infected it for the greater part of 20 years until ClearChannel goes out of business, record labels stop signing so many mediocre artists and thus require stars to subsidize their failures, and Internet distributors stop treating consumers like criminals before they've committed a crime. Value added services, attention to talented local artists, and a broadening to the musical palette exposed to the public will free us from the Top 40 mentality of American pop.<br />
          <div class="byline">
